**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
Deleting an unused enrich policy while `action.destructive_requires_name: true` is in effect fails with the following exception:
```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "illegal_argument_exception",
        "reason" : "Wildcard expressions or all indices are not allowed"
      }
    ],
    "type" : "illegal_argument_exception",
    "reason" : "Wildcard expressions or all indices are not allowed"
  },
  "status" : 400
}
```
After transiently setting `action.destructive_requires_name: false` the deletion is successful:
```
{
  "acknowledged" : true
}
```

**Steps to reproduce**:
1. Create source index:
```
POST /gh-51228/_doc
{
  "field": "value"
}
```
2. Create enrich policy:
```
PUT /_enrich/policy/gh-51228
{
    "match": {
        "indices": [
            "gh-51228"
        ],
        "match_field": "field",
        "enrich_fields": [
            "field"
        ]
    }
}
```
3. Activate enrich policy:
```
PUT /_enrich/policy/gh-51228/_execute
```
4. Disable wildcard deletes:
```
PUT /_cluster/settings
{
  "transient" : {
    "action" : {
      "destructive_requires_name" : "true"
    }
  }
}
```
5. Delete enrich policy:
```
DELETE /_enrich/policy/gh-51228
```

Spotted in 7.6.0

When creating a new trained model, if `trained_model.ensemble.trained_models`  is an empty array, ES responds with a `500`:

**Request:**
```
PUT _ml/inference/foo
{
  "input": {
    "field_names": "fieldy_mc_fieldname"
  },
  "definition": {
    "trained_model": {
      "ensemble": {
        "feature_names": [],
        "trained_models": []
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Response:**
```
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "no_such_element_exception",
        "reason" : "No value present"
      }
    ],
    "type" : "no_such_element_exception",
    "reason" : "No value present"
  },
  "status" : 500
}
```

**ES log output:**
[es_log_output.log](https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch/files/4103563/es_log_output.log)

**Expected behavior:** 
Return a `400` and a meaningful error message that explains what went wrong while parsing the trained model configuration.

**Elasticsearch version**:
`Version: 7.5.1, Build: default/tar/3ae9ac9a93c95bd0cdc054951cf95d88e1e18d96/2019-12-16T22:57:37.835892Z, JVM: 11.0.5`

**JVM version**:
`OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM AdoptOpenJDK (build 11.0.5+10, mixed mode)`

**OS version**:
`Linux 3.10.0-1062.1.2.el7.x86_64 #1 SMP Mon Sep 16 14:19:51 EDT 2019 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 GNU/Linux`

**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
The `set_security_user` processor simply overwrites an already existing target field provided in `field` instead of merging it with existing data and only overwriting the fields specified in `properties`.

I'm not sure if this is a bug or works as intended, but at least the [documentation](https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/reference/current/ingest-node-set-security-user-processor.html) should then make clear that an existing field's data is lost when using this processor.

**Steps to reproduce**:
1. Simulate pipeline
```
POST /_ingest/pipeline/_simulate?verbose=true
{
  "docs": [
    {
      "_index": "gh-51428",
      "_source": {
        "user" : {
          "id": "123",
          "name": "testuser",
          "email": "test@user"
        }
      }
    }
  ],
  "pipeline": {
    "processors": [
      {
        "set_security_user": {
          "field": "user",
          "properties": [
            "username"
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
```
2. Result
```
{
  "docs" : [
    {
      "processor_results" : [
        {
          "doc" : {
            "_index" : "gh-51428",
            "_type" : "_doc",
            "_id" : "_id",
            "_source" : {
              "user" : {
                "username" : "someuser"
              }
            },
            "_ingest" : {
              "timestamp" : "2020-01-24T15:55:40.964116Z"
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```
